      <h1 class="h4">Filter Documents by Regular Expression</h1>
      <form class="form-inline" ng-submit="run()">
        <div class="form-group">
          <div class="input-group">
            <input
              type="text"
              class="form-control ng-pristine ng-valid"
              ng-model="query.regex"
              placeholder="Enter a regular expression, like [A-Z]+"
              ng-readonly="query.running" />
            <span class="input-group-btn">
              <button class="btn btn-default" type="submit" ng-disabled="!canSearch()">Filter</button>
            </span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </form>
      <ul class="instructions">
        <li>Use <a href='https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Guide/Regular_Expressions' target='_parent'>JavaScript&rsquo;s syntax</a></li>
        <li>Don&rsquo;t enter delimiters (e.g. <code>/</code>) around your pattern</li>
        <li>Matches are always case-sensitive, that is, the <code>i</code> flag is not enabled.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="alert" ng-show="status.message" ng-class="status.type">
        <p ng-bind-html="status.message"></p>
      </div>
      </section>
      <section class="new">
        <h1 class="h5">New to Regular Expressions?</h1>
        <p>If you&rsquo;re new to regular expressions, check out this <a href='http://regexr.com/' target='_parent'>learning resource</a> or try the following example patterns:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><a ng-click='query.regex="(^|\\b)[A-Z]+(\\b|$)"'>(^|\b)[A-Z]+(\b|$)</a> matches words that are in all caps</li>
          <li><a ng-click='query.regex="[A-Z]{2,}"'>[A-Z]{2,}</a> matches two or more consecutive capital letters</li>
        </ul>
      </section>
